      "writtenOn": "2020-04-30T15:01:11Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I totally agree that we don\u0027t want an explosion of mutex types, but I don\u0027t think anyone expects that would be the goal or end state. Ideally we could choose our ideal/canonical mutex types and then refactor out the ones that don\u0027t work for us.\n\nI\u0027m unfamiliar with the Sk synchronization types; are you saying they are not interchangeable with absl\u0027s types? Are they implemented in terms of OS primitives? std:: synchronization primitives? Something else?\n\n\u003c\u003c\nYes, if the containers depend on absl::Mutex or dynamic_annotations, then this is fatal.  I\u0027d double check that, because if a container data structure really depends on absl::Mutex or dynamic_annotations, then that\u0027s an indication of poor design and a second reason to not use absl.\n\u003e\u003e\nThe container itself doesn\u0027t use locks. The container headers reference other headers which pull in locks. (The \"other header\" that comes to mind is for hashtablez. Hashtablez is for hashtable debugging/optimization info that we are unlikely to need, but that\u0027s how the reference is formed.)\n\nI think it\u0027s premature to point to absl as poorly designed. It\u0027s got some of the brightest minds in Google working on it and has benchmarks to back up its claims. \n\n\u003c\u003c\nabsl::Mutex is a crutch for Google3 developers used to its pre-standard behavior.  \n\u003e\u003e\nThis is the first I\u0027ve heard anyone complain about absl::Mutex. Could you explain your concern?  I am pretty sure the absl::Mutex design choices were quite intentional. They deviate from std:: but not simply because they are \"pre-standard\" but as a thoughtful choice.",
      "parentUuid": "6c396795_0a15c4f5",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 11,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 13,
        "endChar": 69
      },
      "revId": "2e6e8b853eeb43bf75ad331b6bcea58f66ed1dea",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "d5d7553e_02ee2f0f",
        "filename": "third_party/absl/BUILD.gn",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 13,
      "author": {
        "id": 5045
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-04-30T15:21:33Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "We cannot use flat_hash_map as long as it depends on hashtablez.  btree_map looks fine.\n\nThe absl::Mutex reflects the design of Google\u0027s pre-Abseil, pre-C++11 Mutex.  It\u0027s true that it\u0027s design was intentional and ended up different from std::mutex and std::shared_mutex, better in some ways, worse in others.  But the reason it still exists is because code can not be easily ported away from it; anything else you read is a doublethink post-hoc justification.  It\u0027s similar to why exceptions are not used in Google3.  Google3 is trapped and we need not trap ourselves.\n\nIt absolutely is poor design to require a data structure to depend on a global statistic sampling system.  This whole feature is ancillary and requiring it and its dependencies will hurt the adoption of what is otherwise a very good data structure.\n\nI think you may want to table this for a year or so until you become more familiar with Skia through active feature work?  This sort of refactoring and support work is not a good way to learn the meat of the system.",
      "parentUuid": "3cc86b49_b9d3fe68",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 11,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 13,
        "endChar": 69
